5< /rating>
< Review>
We went on Labor Day and I can honestly say it was a most pleasant experience! Wasn't crowded at all. Life guards were attentive but without the usual constant whistle blowing and yelling. I witnessed one guard gently pulling a kid aside to talk to him about not running. They also allow you to do trick jumps off the high dive.
The restrooms were tidy and the grounds beautiful. Love love live this place and for $4 for an adult, $3 for a child...can't beat the heat for less!
Great time had by all!<//Review>

< review>
The swimming accommodations are excellent there. With about 5-6 swimming areas in several pools, there‚Äôs something for everyone... from water slides, diving boards and a special kids swim area with water play structure. The facilities are clean and there are plenty of lifeguards on duty at all times. There is a fee for entry into the facilities, but getting a season pass or family pass can save you a bundle... and the price is reasonable! Highly recommended for families.< /review>

<review>Honestly the Redding Aquatic Center is okay and their pricing is fair, but some things have happened there with family friends that I think could have been prevented if it was watched more. < review>
This place.... Came here for a xmas party. Needs to be renovated. Food was less than mediocre. We had mexican food...bleh. I am a fan of mexican food also I enjoy a little spice. But if you're catering to a group of diverse people of different backgrounds there should be multiple options and the food should not be spicy AF. Place was very dim so I cant judge ambiance of the hall (maybe a good thing) but by the looks of the outside you would think its abandoned. I would not hold a function here or even come to another function here.<//review>

< text>
Had dinner here on Valentine‚Äôs Day. The staff was very nice and we were given a rose on our way out. That was a sweet gesture. Unfortunately the food was not so good. We started with an order of fried artichoke hearts. The batter was crispy but had no flavor.  The artichoke hearts were either out of a can or jar because they were very soft. For $16 (7 half hearts, not whole) I would expect fresh. So that was disappointing. We then ordered the Orecchiette with sausage and broccoli rabe as well as the eggplant parm. The pasta was not orecchiette but instead was shells. A little disappointing. But more disappointing was that the pasta was overcooked and the only flavor was the overpowering flavor of garlic, and I like garlic. The eggplant parm was okay but was swimming in sauce. We will not be returning to this restaurant.<//text>

Quaint little Italian Restaurant in a strip mall atmosphere, located just outside the Marriott Desert Springs Resort. Prices here are less than in the resort or other restaurants near by. The food was delicious, and served with a small plate of bread, witch olive oil and vinegar. My wife got the capalini lilo dish, and wasn‚Äôt fond of the capers, I thought they were delish. The portion size appeared a bit small though for her dish. I got the Eggplant Parmesan and it was served backed in a lasagna dish, lightly breaded with a fresh homemade marinara sauce, caked in cheese and freshly grated Parmesan offered by our server. You also must try the fried artichoke hearts, they are to die for (it‚Äôs the marinara sauce the makes the dish).<//Review>

I go to Custom Fit for both the "Personal Training" and the "Nutrition" and they both get a resounding 5 stars from me.

Nutrition:
I work with Tarah Venn, who is an incredibly thoughtful and adept nutritionist and has already helped me make more progress in the 2 months I've been working with her than I made in the last 2 years on my own. She promotes long-term habits as opposed to "quick tips" to reach goals quickly. If you're interested in getting some help to reach your dietary goals, I couldn't recommend her more highly.

I work with Kendra Africa, who has been a perfect match for me in terms of personal training. She's customized all of my workouts to optimize strengthening muscles where I've long had weaknesses. I also have dealt with multiple knee injuries and Kendra has been so helpful finding ways to prevent future injuries. She clearly has a vested interest in my success and that's really awesome.<//review>

<resp>None< /resp><text>Let me start off by telling you how NICE this studio is. Beautiful, bright, airy, clean, sleek, simple, welcoming, and fully-equipped. I've been lifting weights, taking classes, and playing sports (including high-level and very competitive) for much of my life, and Custom Fit stands out and stands apart from the many, many places I've exercised. It's a place that makes you want to work hard and do a few extra reps, just because it's such a great environment.

From the moment you walk in the door, Evan and Marissa and their staff are friendly, genuine, low-key, extremely knowledgable, and highly professional. Don't let the laid back demeanor fool you, though; These are people who are serious in their quest to provide the full, personalized health experience for the widest possible range of people. Whether you're training for something specific, or re-evaluating your exercise routine, or just needing a little help, or changing your whole life around, this is the place.

It is immediately evident that the trainers are extremely knowledgeable about fitness, nutrition (especially Marissa, what a gem), and general healthy lifestyle choices. They work together with each client (and with each other) to create a personalized, informative, understandable, and achievable set of goals, and then commit themselves to helping each person achieve them. I can't say enough good about the stuff here. They're the best I've found, hands down.

I also love that the studio is really clean (the complete opposite of those grungy training studios and gyms that are supposed to be "authentic," but are actually just gross). Floors, ceilings, and everything in between is state of the art, functions perfectly, and is extremely well-maintained. The bathroom and shower are excellent. The equipment includes some things you're probably familiar with, and some things you probably aren't; the trainers here are experts in using it all in creative ways to help each person make the most of their training experience.

Lastly, just some little things that especially stand out: they'll wash your gym clothes for you! No more sweaty clothes sitting in your car while you're at work all day. So underrated, and a great perk. Also, great music on a real stereo system! None of the standard box-gym garbage played on tinny little speakers. As you can tell, I'm a big fan of SF's newest (and by far nicest) personal training studio. It's the total package, and more. < userid>
109048349228862513567<//userid>
<user_name>Scott Cheney<//user_name>< Time>
1465276516630<//Time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
This place is amazing for those who're environmentally responsible. They accept hazardous waste like electronics, chemicals, expired medication, biohazard materials. If you use a sharps container for used diabetic supplies, they'll accept your sharps container and replace it free of charge (which I've been told is a rarity as most other places will charge you a disposal fee). The process is very pain free, typically you drive up, hand over your undesirables, issue your John Hancock, and be on your merry way. No need to step out of your vehicle. The staff on hand are very friendly. You actually have no excuses not to use this place.</Review>

<Name>Brenda Hansen<//Name><time>1622735970645</time><Rate>5< /Rate><text>If you are looking for a barn cat, or even a companion cat, I highly recommend LYFF.   We have adopted 4 cats over a course of a year from their barn cat program.  They delivered the cats to us, provided advice and after care (one of our cats had a runny nose and they provided antibiotics) and even provided a nice care package with the last two.

Some of the cats only spend a few days in the shelter, but one of them was about ready to be euthanized before he was brought to us.  This gives the cats a chance at the life they want to live--even though being outdoors is still a risk for them--that's where they came from originally without being spayed or neutered, or having a steady source of food and water.  Most of the cats warmed up to humans pretty quickly.  We even have one that hangs out with us all day and follows us around the ranch and sleeps on our front porch.

The interaction with the staff/volunteers at LYFF has been very positive and they really care about their cats.</text><pics>None< /pics><Resp>None<//Resp><gmap_id>0x80dc77fc3123c3a1:0x4c69767941fcc0< /gmap_id></record>

< user>
102907809009131768964<//user>
<username>Faith E< /username><Time>1621670095005< /Time><Rating>1<//Rating><review>We love fur babies and were referred to LYFF by a colleague as a great organization to adopt a kitten (or two!)

We had high hopes for adopting two seemingly bonded kitties but have been sorely disappointed by the adoption process, lack of consistent follow up and what feels like arbitrary application of implementation of unusual filtering.

For example, there is question about whether renter vs owner and if landlord approves you having pets. These are normal and customary questions. What is unusual is a seemingly rigid halt to application process to reach out to an applicant's landlord to gain 3rd party consent for having pets. As a quite seasoned and mature adult, it is unusual to have an organization seeking confirmation from a person's landlord where things like this are already stipulated, outlined, or addressed in one's lease. To me (though still invasive), a copy of lease would be better avenue as landlords aren't accustomed to 3rd parties contacting them about pet adoption for their tenants.

Nonetheless, it took two follow ups from me and a direct ask about the two kitties we were seeking to adopt before I received a reply stating that they were waiting for my landlord to reply to them and that the two kittens we'd applied for were adopted out to someone else. I understand understaffing and high volume as I work as a Manager for a major Branded hotel but to not proactively inform an applicant that the kittens they're applying for were being redirected felt like a slap and severely insensitive.

Since receiving the info that the two kittens we had applied for were adopted out to someone else, we've received zero feedback, follow up, or reply. Particularly during these times, I find it difficult to believe that our application was halted because of a landlord reply when there are many alternatives to confirming, proving pet allowance. No other cat adoption organization or humane society appears to function in this manner.

Perhaps this was a one off process for us which was quite unfortunate.

I love sharing great experiences and positive stories. This experience however has fallen harshly short in so many ways.

Hopefully others will have a better adoption journey with LYFF than we did.</review><pictures>None</pictures><resp>None<//resp>< gmap_id>

< Time>
1571242238046<//Time>
<rating>5</rating>< review>
Love Your Feral Felines is a great organization very clear and transparent. All the members have been friendly and great to work with.
They are all about providing a home to cats/kittens and saving feral cats lives.
They have two programs to save lives.
-Adoption program: For social cats/kittens to find suitable indoor homes they partner with Petsmart, Vet Offices and Cat Cafe to foster adoption of cats/kittens.
-Barn Cat program (no kittens): to rescue feral non-social cats from shelters that would otherwise be euthanized (no-kill does not apply to feral cats) and provide them barn homes to foster rodent control. They train barn owners on how to successfully adapt the cats to their new environment. This is part of their TNR program as well.< /review>

The cats and kittens available for adoption at our outreach events are part of our Foster & Adoption Program and are social felines looking for safe indoor homes. Our Barn Cat Program saves feral felines from euthanasia at local shelters and places them into outdoor homes. Those particular kittens at our outreach event Sunday were hand-raised and have never been exposed to the dangers of outside. They would not have survived in the environment. < text>
My favorite Greek restaurant in the South Bay. Food is consistently delicious. Service is great. The owner is a very good man, and makes you feel at home. When I first ate here as a kid, the owner let me, my brother, and my friend take a picture holding a replica of the Olympic torch from the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens. < Text>
Right before my predecessor retired she said this restaurant is one of the Company favorites. To find a restaurant where everyone enjoys the food with no complaints is no small feat with this office.

Taki the Catering Director is awesome and always responds to my (multiple) questions and changes quickly. The Tri Tip (Moschari Psito) is amazing. Both of the chicken dishes that I have ordered (Chicken Souvlaki and Reganati) are phenomenal. All meats are always cooked perfectly, even with ordering for nearly 100. Everything is cooked perfectly including the rice and grilled vegetables. They don't skimp on the portions either. Thank you all so much!</Text>

< Text>
I got lamb souvlaki plate and my gf got gyro wrap. They also bring complimentary plates, and my review for each here:

Complimentary plates:
They bring complimentary salad, humus and pita plate. They have deep fried pita (they call it chipped pita) which was included in the complimentary pita plate and it is delicious! They were kind enough to bring more of chipped pita when we asked for it. There was too much garlic in the hummus, it was like a garlic paste as opposed to hummus lol. But hey it was complimentary.

Main plates:
Lamb souvlaki tasted a bit dry, but it was still okay. It comes with rice and veggies.  The gyro in my gf's wrap was delicious, it was thick yet tender. It came with fries which were also delicious.

I should also add that service here was great, it was quick and the server was very responsive.</Text>

110499392629231906894<//user_id>
<Text>First visit after seeing this place reviewed on "Check, Please! Bay Area" and the show's unanimous positive reviews were spot on.

Decided to have a weekday lunch, went early, around 11:20a to beat the peak lunch crowd. The ordering line gets long very quickly around 11:45a and available table seating sparse soon thereafter.

My wife ordered the "Swordfish Souvlaki Wrap" and I the "Lamb Souvlaki Plate." The swordfish wrap was a bit messy to eat by hand with the fish and sauce juices dripping. The fish was seasoned well, not overly salted. Overall, delicious. The lamb plate came with a Greek style salad, sauteed veggies, decent portion side of rice, single kabob of well seasoned lamb. Again, tasty and enjoyable.

We plan to revisit and try other dishes.< /Text>< Date>

Always one of my local favorite restaurants. If you're doing strict Keto, get the salmon with extra veggies.

Otherwise, get the Yiro plate with garlic French fries! Yum yum. The purple tart sauce is the perfect dipping sauce for the French fries.

Lunch time bread and hummus is complimentary, and really good. Just come early to secure good table (inside or outside).

The owner is a older, friendly chap. He always stops by every table and ask how the food and service is. 5/5 stars all the way< /text>

<Text>Excellent food - biftekia, wraps, especially lamb pita wrap. You are not going to find lamb wraps/gyro in Greece now days, as the meat is too expensive vs what they can charge. Or you'll find it in the ground mix with more  herbs and fried oil then lamb. And all that  for 12$, in the heart of Silicon  Valley. Seems they make their own hummus and also, raspberry sauce you get with fries is awesome. Fries are extremely good. Seems they use good ingredients and know how to do it...

What's better than in Greece is the gyros comes with fries aside, not in the gyros.

The owner is always around and makes sure everything is right. Same employees for last 10 years tells a lot. Recently they've put lemons and olives around the place to make it look "right". Lots of outdoor seating< /Text>< Pics>

< text>
Counter service restaurant.Food is delivered to the table. Expect just a few words spoken from staff your entire meal.  That will be from the cashier and the server delivering your plate.   Lunch was pretty fast paced.

A server quickly dropped some pita and a few minutes later hummus nary a word and didn't stop. Pita os both fried and plain. Fried was different and of course, good. It is fried bread after all.  Hummus was typical.

Everyone enjoyed their lunch. I had a gyro plate. Meat was both way overcooked and just right. I didn't mind either way. Lunch rush is like that.  Fries were a disappointment being soft. Blah.  Salad was great as was the tzatziki.

I'll come back again. I'd give the place 3.5 stars if I could.<//text>

<UserId.>111900993939235809465< /UserId.><time>1537036464527< /time><Text>Went to this place for the first time, yesterday, because my family saw them on Check Please Bay Area. We went here to celebrate a birthday and were hugely disappointed.

The visit was on Friday 8/14/18, at about 5:00pm . The place wasn't busy.

The food was average at best, but average is being nice.

The complementary meze hummus was the best item we ate. It tasted like it was made in house.

As for our meals.. I had the Gyros Plate. It had a generous amount of meat, tomato and red onion flooded with tzatziki sauce. A little restraint on the sauce would have been nicer. The meat was ok tasting andvedible. The side of Garlic fries had zero taste of garlic, was cold and limp and inedible.

Another member of my family had a plate with fish and shrimp of some kind and was also hugely disappointed. Way too much oil on the plate.

No server came to ask how everything  was, because we would have told them our fries were cold, limp, and didnt taste of garlic.

We couldn't get out of here soon enough.

We had hopes we could find a new place we could enjoy and place in our dining rotation, but this was a huge miss for my entire family.</Text>< pics>

Janet Fricke< /user_name>
< time>
1537834861472</time>
<Rating>2<//Rating>< review>
I was excited to visit this eatery for seeing it on Check Please on PBS this weekend. While waiting in line to order (you order first, then find a table to sit)I saw delicious plates go buy. Unfortunately what I ordered was not freshly made. I had the combination platter. I was told they ran out of Pastitsio so I could substitute more Spanakopita or Mousaka or stuffed grape leaves. Unfortunately the Spanakopita and Moussaka were reheated, soggy and tasted rewarmed- not fresh. The french fries were also "limp and soggy" and "not crispy hot" and could not stand up to holding them to put into the small dish of delicious kalamata dipping  sauce. I expected the phyllo dough in the spanakopita to have a "crunch" but it was so soggy I had to cut it with a fork. what a disappointment. The Mousaka was not even thoroughly heated through and was dry. I think if I had selected a grilled skewer item cooked to order it would have been a better choice. My husband had the beef tenderloin skewer souvlaki. It was done perfectly to medium rare, juicy and hot.
The staff were very friendly and helpful.  I had told our server that I had just seen the restaurant on Check Please and so excited to come. She said it has been televised 3 times. Truly a disappointment for driving 40 miles one way.</review>
